[1] Cholera: management, commentary
Date: Tue 14 Sep 2010
From: Eduardo Gotuzzo <eduardo.gotuzzo@upch.pe> [edited]


In face of a cholera pandemic in resource-constrained settings (with
poverty, limited conditions of drainage, and scarce health
facilities), efforts should be implemented at different levels:

1. At the community level, health care of all patients with diarrhea
but no vomiting:
- use oral rehydration salts, which must be started immediately,
encouraging drink of water every 30-60 minutes, provided the patient
continues without vomiting;
- oral rehydration salts should be prepared with safe, clean water,
either drinking water or chlorinated water (tap water with 1 drop of
hypochlorite solution per 10 liters of water). Also, the tap water
can be boiled and then covered for 2-4 hours so it can recover
ambient oxygen and its typical taste;
- for this activity, mothers should be encouraged to stimulate and
provide oral rehydration both to their children but also to adult
relatives.
2. Patients treated at the community level should be referred to the
health centers when there is vomiting, or diarrheas with increasing
volumes. For the latter case, oral rehydration should be reinforced
and closely observed, and the patient should receive antibiotics for
3 days (antibiotics help to diminish the number and the volume of
stools).
3. If the patient does not respond well to oral rehydration, he or
she should be treated at mini-hospitals or hospitals, with
intravenous rehydration therapy containing sodium chloride (0.9
percent). The goal is to keep the diuresis, and to start again with
oral rehydration therapy as soon as the patient recovers enough to
tolerate it.
4. The sitting position (far more than typical cholera cots) reduces
aspiration pneumonia and vomiting, and facilitates moving on with the
oral rehydration. Such a simple method is of extraordinary help.
5. Finally, given a dramatic situation such as that observed in Goma,
Congo DR (of very high mortality, exceeding more than 20 000 deaths),
I would consider recommending, in addition to the measures indicated
above, the use of prophylaxis in all cohabitants of a home where
there is a cholera case. One tablet of fluoroquinolones, such as
ciprofloxacin, reaches adequate concentration in stools for more than
2-4 days and thus stands as a quite good option for prophylaxis. In
my opinion, this measure should not generate a drug resistance
phenomenon, even considering massive use.

--
Dr Eduardo Gotuzzo
Director
Instituto de Medicina Tropical
Alexander von Humboldt
Universidad Peruana Cayetano Heredia
Peru
<eduardo.gotuzzo@upch.pe>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Gotuzzo for his timely commentary on
management of this potentially fatal infection. - Mod.LL]

